I applied the max-width behavior to img, svg in particular, but perhaps it should be applied to the outer element, or all children of output. It is not clear to me whether raw HTML output (e.g. iframes) be restricted, or left alone. Perhaps a combination of this and #7718 should be used.

For the moment, I'm inclined to only confine images. The reason being that we already have the double-click to expand behavior on images (I only changed slightly what expand means in this PR), but not on the output area as a whole. That means that right now, there's an easy way to expand larger images to their native size, but not an easy way to expand other HTML elements. Perhaps we should go that way ultimately, but I like to take these things one step at a time.

@takluyver thanks for pointing that out, yes calc should fix it in the latest commit. I thought it was behaving correctly because of my custom css changes the right margin. I should really remember to test CSS PRs without custom CSS.

@takluyver I don't think it should be different to set widths and heights in an iframe than importing an image of arbitrary size. The container should constraint the output's dimensions under any circumstance. Actually, if you change the iframe to have `width:100%;` that fixes it. However, I think it is better to clean that part of the markup to make it more consistent and allow for a more definitive solution. For example, even relatively simple HTML will overflow (in the example below, a table):

![screenshot from 2015-03-18 17 29 21](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/599274/6721600/8d3cb8e4-cd94-11e4-9769-12bb523b4c65.png)

@minrk I think the double click (and single click) behavior is working correctly in other HTML elements (actually, in the case of a table, the double click works but single click has no effect.) The main problem are not the parent elements. The problem is that the HTML tags that are injected need to have proper styling to fit their parents.

I finally understood the thing that is causing problems. It is the `.resizable()` [method](http://jqueryui.com/resizable/) from jquery-ui. Particularly, the following lines:

```
        //Create a wrapper element and set the wrapper to the new current internal element
        this.element.wrap(
            $("<div class='ui-wrapper' style='overflow: hidden;'></div>").css({
                position: this.element.css("position"),
                width: this.element.outerWidth(),
                height: this.element.outerHeight(),
                top: this.element.css("top"),
                left: this.element.css("left")
            })
        );

        //Overwrite the original this.element
        this.element = this.element.parent().data(
            "ui-resizable", this.element.data("ui-resizable")
        );
```

This is setting a width and height in pixels to the element `ui-wrapper`:

![screenshot from 2015-03-19 16 28 38](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/599274/6742580/8e487e9a-ce56-11e4-84e9-0cad3c9a9d85.png)

Therefore, when we resize the window, the old width and height remain. This is also adding a class `ui-resizable` to the image element with the same width and height than `ui-wrapper`. By the way, this is the resize handler that  @jdfreder was referring to in the first place.

I was wondering whether we really need that feature. I didn't even know it existed.
